{"id":"2206.11796","submitter":"Bernhard Hanke","authors":"Simone Cecchini, Bernhard Hanke, Thomas Schick","title":"Lipschitz rigidity for scalar curvature","comments":"29 pages, proof of invariance of scalar curvature distribution under\n  metric isometries added, minor changes and corrections, bibliography updated","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG math.MG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We prove the following Lipschitz rigidity result in scalar curvature\ngeometry. Let $M$ be a closed smooth connected spin manifold of even dimension\n$n$, let $g$ be a Riemannian metric of regularity $W^{1,p}$, $p > n$, on $M$\nwhose distributional scalar curvature in the sense of Lee-LeFloch is bounded\nbelow by $n(n-1)$, and let $f \\colon (M,g) \\to \\mathbb{S}^n$ be a $1$-Lipschitz\ncontinuous (not necessarily smooth) map of non-zero degree to the unit\n$n$-sphere. Then $f$ is a metric isometry. This generalizes a result of Llarull\n(1998) and answers in the affirmative a question of Gromov (2019) in his \"four\nlectures\".\n  Our proof is based on spectral properties of Dirac operators for low\nregularity Riemannian metrics and twisted with Lipschitz bundles. We argue that\nthe existence of a non-zero harmonic spinor field forces $f$ to be quasiregular\nin the sense of Reshetnyak, and in this way connect the powerful theory for\nquasiregular maps to the Atiyah-Singer index theorem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 23 Jun 2022 16:03:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 24 Jun 2022 07:51:30 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 27 Jul 2022 14:07:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-28"}
